04102nam a22006015i 9789048550968DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485509687 a10.1515/97890485509682doi  a(DE-B1597)617081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1995.9.E18 7aART0570002bisacsh04a791.432231 aLuca, Tiago, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlanetary Cinema :bFilm, Media and the Earth /cTiago Luca. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (330 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1 Sublime Earth -- t2 The Unseen World Across the World -- t3 The Universal Equality of Things -- t4 The Face of the World -- t5 A Networked Humanity -- t6 A Disappearing Planet -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe story is now familiar. In the late 1960s humanity finally saw photographic evidence of the Earth in space for the first time. According to this narrative, the impact of such images in the consolidation of a planetary consciousness is yet to be matched. This book tells a different story. It argues that this narrative has failed to account for the vertiginous global imagination underpinning the media and film culture of the late nineteenth century and beyond. Panoramas, giant globes, world exhibitions, photography and stereography: all promoted and hinged on the idea of a world made whole and newly visible. When it emerged, cinema did not simply contribute to this effervescent globalism so much as become its most significant and enduring manifestation. Planetary Cinema proposes that an exploration of that media culture can help us understand contemporary planetary imaginaries in times of environmental collapse. Engaging with a variety of media, genres and texts, the book sits at the intersection of film/media history and theory/philosophy, and it claims that we need this combined approach and expansive textual focus in order to understand the way we see the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aTransnational and Global Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aEarth, World, Global consciousness, Cinema, Media archaeology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048550968zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048550968zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048550968/original  a978-3-11-074322-7 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7 DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA